{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491120"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:33:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:33:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"837"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/837"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.05,0.03,0.79,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43990"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/837"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28978"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2746"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45059"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43990","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43990"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner for a routine health check. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is a non-smoker. She has no family history of thyroid or autoimmune conditions. On physical examination a 2 cm diameter smooth-surfaced and soft swelling 3 cm below and 2 cm to the right of her hyoid is noted. Her TSH level is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fine needle aspiration cytology","Thyroid scintigraphy","CT scan neck","Ultrasound","Sestamibi scan"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis swelling is probably a prominent nodule in the thyroid, as it is smooth and soft, and contiguous with the rest of the thyroid. \u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E should be the initial mode of imaging for the identification of posteriorly located nodules or predominantly cystic nodules. If a nodule is identified, cytological examination through a \u003Cstrong\u003Efine needle aspiration\u003C/strong\u003E (FNA) could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the TSH level is low, a \u003Cstrong\u003Ethyroid scintigraphy\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a nuclear medicine scan involving the intravenous injection of radio-labelled technetium preferentially taken up by thyroid tissue is performed. This would not be the appropriate investigation for this case, as scintigraphy is usually reserved for the determination of hypofunctional hyperthyroidism which would need to be further investigated with FNA to assess for malignancy. However, this is contraindicated in pregnancy due to its radioactivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT Neck\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate when attempting to stage a suspected malignancy (i.e., looking for lymphadenopathy, or local metastasis), however this patient has no symptoms consistent with this (e.g. dysphonia from recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy, dyspnoea, dysphagia), making this the incorrect choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ESestamibi scan\u003C/strong\u003E is another type of nuclear medicine scan, useful in the evaluation of suspected parathyroid malignancy. This patient has no signs or symptoms consistent with hypercalcaemia, or any other features suggestive of malignancy, making this the incorrect choice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Ultrasound is the most appropriate initial investigation for a newly-identified thyroid nodule.","A TSH should be performed prior to any imaging of a suspected thyroid nodule, to exclude hyper- or hypothyroidism."],"references":["Venkatesh N, Ho JT. Investigating thyroid nodules. Australian Prescriber. 2021;44(6):200. Available at: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/investigating-thyroid-nodules.html","Lee JC, Harris AM, Khafagi FA. Thyroid scans. Australian Family Physician. 2012;41(8):584-6. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/980fb2e2-ccdd-4851-a2dd-393bf0f945c4/Thyroid-scans.aspx","Bailey S, Wallwork B. Differentiating between benign and malignant thyroid nodules: An evidence-based approach in general practice. Australian Journal of General Practice. 2018;47(11):770-4. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/november/differentiating-between-benign-and-malignant-t-1"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"837"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28978"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-03T22:11:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-03T22:11:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"837"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43990"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":n